it's how perfectly it describes the psychological traps

48
00:01:55,583 --> 00:01:57,875
we all fall into every single day

49
00:01:58,083 --> 00:02:00,666
even with our modern technology and lifestyles

50
00:02:05,666 --> 00:02:06,833
picture this

51
00:02:07,083 --> 00:02:09,958
the future Buddha sitting under the Bodhi tree

52
00:02:10,166 --> 00:02:12,625
determined to find the answer to all suffering

53
00:02:13,083 --> 00:02:16,125
the night is dark stars filling the sky

54
00:02:16,333 --> 00:02:17,083
and Siddhartha

55
00:02:17,083 --> 00:02:19,125
Gautama is this close to breaking through

56
00:02:19,125 --> 00:02:20,500
to complete enlightenment

57
00:02:21,000 --> 00:02:23,208
but suddenly the air shifts

58
00:02:23,583 --> 00:02:26,291
something's coming something powerful

59
00:02:26,458 --> 00:02:28,916
and it does not want Buddha to succeed

60
00:02:29,541 --> 00:02:31,750
Mara's voice slithers through the darkness

61
00:02:32,083 --> 00:02:33,375
turn back princeling

62
00:02:33,583 --> 00:02:36,541
this path leads nowhere your kingdom awaits you

63
00:02:36,541 --> 00:02:39,916
your family needs you why torture yourself for nothing

64
00:02:40,208 --> 00:02:41,875
this is Mara

65
00:02:43,583 --> 00:02:45,208
in that legendary night

66
00:02:45,291 --> 00:02:47,375
as Buddha sat in deep meditation

67
00:02:47,541 --> 00:02:49,916
Mara unleashed everything he had

68
00:02:50,083 --> 00:02:53,000
first his demon armies with weapons and fire

69
00:02:53,083 --> 00:02:55,208
then powerful storms and earthquakes

70
00:02:55,791 --> 00:02:57,791
but Buddha remained unmoved

71
00:02:59,000 --> 00:03:01,750
seriously the guy didn't even flinch

72
00:03:02,416 --> 00:03:04,125
when physical attacks failed

73
00:03:04,500 --> 00:03:06,250
Mara tried something smarter

74
00:03:06,416 --> 00:03:07,958
he sent his three daughters

75
00:03:08,250 --> 00:03:09,875
to seduce and distract Buddha

76
00:03:09,875 --> 00:03:12,250
with the three things humans can rarely resist

77
00:03:12,708 --> 00:03:16,125
craving boredom and lust

78
00:03:17,208 --> 00:03:19,583
ancient texts describe them as appearing in forms

79
00:03:19,583 --> 00:03:21,666
designed to appeal to different temperaments

80
00:03:21,875 --> 00:03:23,583
sometimes as alluring dancers

81
00:03:23,708 --> 00:03:25,458
sometimes as nurturing mothers

82
00:03:25,541 --> 00:03:27,208
sometimes as wise teachers

83
00:03:27,583 --> 00:03:29,041
whatever form would most likely

84
00:03:29,041 --> 00:03:31,250
succeed in pulling Buddha from his meditation

85
00:03:31,250 --> 00:03:32,250
they would assume

86
00:03:32,708 --> 00:03:35,041
yet their true power wasn't in their appearance

87
00:03:35,125 --> 00:03:37,166
but in the mental states they evoked

88
00:03:37,958 --> 00:03:40,250
but we'll get to those temptresses in a minute

89
00:03:40,666 --> 00:03:43,208
so who exactly is this Mara character

90
00:03:43,375 --> 00:03:46,791
in Buddhist tradition Mara isn't just some random demon

91
00:03:47,000 --> 00:03:49,375
he's basically the Lord of death itself

92
00:03:49,750 --> 00:03:52,458
his name literally means destroyer

93
00:03:52,791 --> 00:03:54,041
he represents everything

94
00:03:54,041 --> 00:03:56,125
that keeps us trapped in cycles of suffering

95
00:03:56,583 --> 00:03:58,333
but here's where it gets interesting

96
00:03:58,333 --> 00:04:00,666
and very different from the Christian Satan

97
00:04:01,375 --> 00:04:02,500
Mara isn't some separate

98
00:04:02,500 --> 00:04:04,541
evil force battling against good

99
00:04:04,666 --> 00:04:06,666
he's more like the voice in your head saying

100
00:04:06,666 --> 00:04:09,666
just one more episode just one more cookie

101
00:04:09,791 --> 00:04:12,083
just check Instagram one more time

102
00:04:12,541 --> 00:04:14,541
he's not trying to steal your soul

103
00:04:14,833 --> 00:04:16,750
he's trying to steal your attention

104
00:04:17,041 --> 00:04:19,541
your focus your mental freedom

105
00:04:20,125 --> 00:04:21,708
in Buddhist cosmology

106
00:04:21,875 --> 00:04:24,750
Mara rules over the highest heaven of the desire realm

107
00:04:25,083 --> 00:04:26,166
imagine that

108
00:04:26,416 --> 00:04:28,833
the Buddhist devil lives in a kind of heaven

109
00:04:29,541 --> 00:04:31,166
this tells us something super

110
00:04:31,166 --> 00:04:33,083
important about Buddhist psychology

111
00:04:33,500 --> 00:04:35,291
the most dangerous traps

112
00:04:35,291 --> 00:04:37,458
often disguise themselves as pleasures

113
00:04:38,125 --> 00:04:41,125
now there's a big debate among Buddhist scholars

114
00:04:41,375 --> 00:04:44,041
was Mara a literal demon that Buddha faced

115
00:04:44,250 --> 00:04:46,625
or was he a personification of Buddha's own

116
00:04:46,625 --> 00:04:49,875
internal struggles the mental obstacles we all face

117
00:04:50,500 --> 00:04:53,750
the coolest part it doesn't really matter

118
00:04:54,250 --> 00:04:56,166
because whether Mara is real

119
00:04:56,208 --> 00:04:58,000
or just a powerful metaphor

120
00:04:58,250 --> 00:04:59,916
the effect is the same

121
00:05:00,375 --> 00:05:03,291
he represents the forces that keep us from freedom

122
00:05:03,916 --> 00:05:04,416
consider

123
00:05:04,416 --> 00:05:06,833
the last time you were determined to start a new habit

124
00:05:06,833 --> 00:05:10,583
maybe meditation or exercise or eating better

125
00:05:10,958 --> 00:05:14,333
but then something pulled you away

126
00:05:14,916 --> 00:05:16,583
something distracted you

127
00:05:16,916 --> 00:05:18,291
something made you doubt yourself

128
00:05:19,333 --> 00:05:20,500
that was Mara

129
00:05:21,083 --> 00:05:23,708
and what makes Mara scarier than the western devil

130
00:05:23,833 --> 00:05:25,666
Satan tempts you to break rules

131
00:05:25,916 --> 00:05:28,166
Mara tempts you to break promises to yourself

132
00:05:28,708 --> 00:05:30,750
Satan wants your soul in the afterlife

133
00:05:30,916 --> 00:05:32,791
Mara wants your mind right now

134
00:05:33,750 --> 00:05:35,541
in the famous Sutta Nipata

135
00:05:35,541 --> 00:05:37,208
an ancient Buddhist text

136
00:05:37,958 --> 00:05:39,916
Buddha describes Mara as

137
00:05:39,916 --> 00:05:42,250
the one who delights in sensual pleasure

138
00:05:42,875 --> 00:05:45,166
not because pleasure itself is bad

139
00:05:45,416 --> 00:05:48,125
but because getting lost in temporary pleasures

140
00:05:48,166 --> 00:05:51,958
keeps us from finding lasting happiness

141
00:05:53,208 --> 00:05:53,958
now

142
00:05:53,958 --> 00:05:56,875
most religious traditions have some kind of evil figure

143
00:05:57,208 --> 00:05:58,458
but Mara is unique

144
00:05:58,458 --> 00:06:00,500
because the Buddha never said to worship anything

145
00:06:00,500 --> 00:06:02,958
to defeat him no rituals

146
00:06:03,166 --> 00:06:06,208
no prayers no special ceremonies

147
00:06:07,125 --> 00:06:09,791
instead the Buddha taught something radical

148
00:06:10,166 --> 00:06:13,833
the way to defeat Mara is simply to see him clearly

149
00:06:14,083 --> 00:06:17,041
to recognize when your mind is being pulled by craving

150
00:06:17,416 --> 00:06:20,166
to notice when you're being manipulated by desire

151
00:06:21,166 --> 00:06:23,166
as Buddha himself supposedly said

152
00:06:23,166 --> 00:06:24,500
I see you Mara

153
00:06:25,000 --> 00:06:26,916
those four words changed everything

154
00:06:27,500 --> 00:06:28,833
because once you see the traps

155
00:06:28,833 --> 00:06:30,500
it loses its power over you

156
00:06:31,750 --> 00:06:33,458
but Mara's greatest strength

157
00:06:33,458 --> 00:06:34,708
his three daughters

158
00:06:34,833 --> 00:06:37,375
each specialized in a different type of temptation

159
00:06:37,708 --> 00:06:39,125
each designed to exploit

160
00:06:39,125 --> 00:06:41,083
a different weakness in the human mind

161
00:06:41,375 --> 00:06:43,958
and that's where our story gets really interesting

162
00:06:48,500 --> 00:06:50,291
so let's meet daughter No. 1

163
00:06:50,583 --> 00:06:53,875
Tanhā whose name literally means thirst or craving

164
00:06:54,125 --> 00:06:55,500
of all of Mara's daughters

165
00:06:55,500 --> 00:06:57,833
she might be the one you spend the most time with

166
00:06:57,875 --> 00:06:59,750
maybe without even realizing it

167
00:07:00,500 --> 00:07:03,000
imagine that feeling when you really want something

168
00:07:03,208 --> 00:07:06,083
like need it that pull in your chest

169
00:07:06,416 --> 00:07:09,000
that sense that you won't be happy until you get it

170
00:07:09,250 --> 00:07:11,166
that's Tanhā working her magic

171
00:07:11,875 --> 00:07:15,500
in the ancient texts Tanhā is described as the maker

172
00:07:15,500 --> 00:07:18,416
of the fetters that bind people to the cycle of rebirth

173
00:07:19,083 --> 00:07:22,416
pretty heavy stuff but in simple terms

174
00:07:22,833 --> 00:07:25,250
she's why you can't eat just one potato chip

175
00:07:26,333 --> 00:07:28,666
Tanhā whispers just one more scroll

176
00:07:28,666 --> 00:07:30,666
one more purchase one more bite

177
00:07:30,791 --> 00:07:32,166
then you'll feel complete

178
00:07:32,750 --> 00:07:35,541
Buddha identified Tanhā as the root cause of suffering

179
00:07:35,541 --> 00:07:37,583
in his famous four noble truths

180
00:07:38,166 --> 00:07:41,458
that's right of all the problems humans face

181
00:07:41,750 --> 00:07:44,041
he pointed to craving as the biggest one

182
00:07:44,500 --> 00:07:46,541
but why is wanting things so bad

183
00:07:46,541 --> 00:07:48,458
don't we need desires to function

184
00:07:48,625 --> 00:07:49,708
to have goals

185
00:07:50,666 --> 00:07:52,625
the Buddha never said desires themselves

186
00:07:52,625 --> 00:07:54,750
were the problem it's clinging to them

187
00:07:54,750 --> 00:07:56,791
the difference is subtle but crucial

188
00:07:57,250 --> 00:08:00,125
think about it like this you want a new phone

189
00:08:00,416 --> 00:08:02,708
nothing wrong with that but then

190
00:08:02,708 --> 00:08:03,666
you become convinced

191
00:08:03,666 --> 00:08:05,625
you can't be happy without that phone

192
00:08:05,791 --> 00:08:07,875
you check prices every day

193
00:08:08,125 --> 00:08:10,125
you imagine how much better life will be

194
00:08:10,125 --> 00:08:13,541
once you have it you get irritated waiting for it

195
00:08:14,166 --> 00:08:15,875
that's when Tanhā has hooked you

196
00:08:15,875 --> 00:08:17,750
and she's gotten so much better at her job

197
00:08:17,750 --> 00:08:20,291
in the modern world social media

198
00:08:20,625 --> 00:08:22,000
Tanhā's playground

199
00:08:22,125 --> 00:08:24,750
every scroll designed to make you want something new

200
00:08:25,000 --> 00:08:27,833
every influencer showing you a life you don't have

201
00:08:27,875 --> 00:08:29,083
every targeted ad

202
00:08:29,083 --> 00:08:31,291
perfectly matched to your secret desires

203
00:08:31,750 --> 00:08:34,416
in an ancient Buddhist text called the Dhammapada

204
00:08:34,416 --> 00:08:37,458
Buddha says from craving springs grief

205
00:08:37,458 --> 00:08:39,083
from craving springs fear

206
00:08:39,166 --> 00:08:41,416
for one who is wholly free from craving

207
00:08:41,666 --> 00:08:44,125
there is no grief much less fear

208
00:08:45,125 --> 00:08:47,375
modern science actually backs this up

209
00:08:47,625 --> 00:08:49,458
studies show that the dopamine hit we get

210
00:08:49,458 --> 00:08:51,541
isn't actually from getting what we want

211
00:08:51,583 --> 00:08:53,541
it comes from the anticipation

212
00:08:53,625 --> 00:08:57,208
the wanting itself that's why satisfaction never lasts

213
00:08:57,541 --> 00:09:00,375
the brain is literally wired to keep wanting more

214
00:09:00,791 --> 00:09:02,041
but here's the twist

215
00:09:02,541 --> 00:09:04,541
Tanhā doesn't just make us want stuff

216
00:09:04,541 --> 00:09:06,166
she comes in three flavors

217
00:09:06,916 --> 00:09:09,833
first there's craving for sensual pleasures

218
00:09:10,083 --> 00:09:12,416
the obvious one food

219
00:09:12,583 --> 00:09:14,666
sex comfort

220
00:09:15,000 --> 00:09:16,375
the newest iPhone

221
00:09:17,041 --> 00:09:17,833
second

222
00:09:18,333 --> 00:09:20,000
there's craving for existence

223
00:09:20,291 --> 00:09:23,166
the desire to be someone to achieve

224
00:09:23,458 --> 00:09:26,083
to be important to leave a mark

225
00:09:26,541 --> 00:09:29,125
think social media followers and career ambition

226
00:09:29,541 --> 00:09:31,791
and third there's the weird one

227
00:09:32,083 --> 00:09:33,625
craving for non existence

228
00:09:33,666 --> 00:09:36,208
the desire to escape to numb out

229
00:09:36,250 --> 00:09:39,833
to not feel this is why we binge Netflix

230
00:09:40,166 --> 00:09:43,333
drink too much or scroll mindlessly for hours

231
00:09:44,208 --> 00:09:46,750
the Buddha taught that all three types keep us trapped

232
00:09:46,791 --> 00:09:49,041
so how do you know when Tanhā is working on you

233
00:09:49,041 --> 00:09:52,583
look for these signs that feeling of I'll be happy when

234
00:09:52,833 --> 00:09:53,791
that's her

235
00:09:54,083 --> 00:09:56,500
that itch to check your phone every five minutes

236
00:09:56,666 --> 00:10:00,291
that's her that sense that what you have isn't enough

237
00:10:00,458 --> 00:10:01,750
definitely her

238
00:10:02,916 --> 00:10:04,250
so how did Buddha recommend

239
00:10:04,250 --> 00:10:05,750
dealing with his first daughter

240
00:10:05,833 --> 00:10:08,666
not by fighting her not by giving in either

241
00:10:08,791 --> 00:10:10,750
but by seeing the craving clearly

242
00:10:10,750 --> 00:10:12,833
and understanding its empty nature

243
00:10:13,083 --> 00:10:15,208
in his own words from the Majjhima Nikaya

244
00:10:15,208 --> 00:10:18,291
whatever in the world is pleasant and agreeable toward

245
00:10:18,291 --> 00:10:19,708
this craving arises

246
00:10:20,166 --> 00:10:23,333
seeing its arising and passing away as it actually is

247
00:10:23,541 --> 00:10:25,500
that's the path to its cessation

248
00:10:25,750 --> 00:10:29,000
simply put when you feel that craving rise up

249
00:10:29,125 --> 00:10:31,333
don't judge it don't fear it

250
00:10:31,416 --> 00:10:33,416
just notice it oh

251
00:10:33,416 --> 00:10:35,708
there's craving watch it rise

252
00:10:35,958 --> 00:10:39,250
watch it eventually fade without acting on it

253
00:10:39,500 --> 00:10:42,416
try this experiment next time you feel a powerful want

254
00:10:43,458 --> 00:10:46,125
set a timer for just 10 minutes before giving in

255
00:10:47,041 --> 00:10:48,833
just observe the feeling

256
00:10:49,791 --> 00:10:52,208
you might be shocked to discover that many cravings

257
00:10:52,208 --> 00:10:53,708
naturally fade on their own

258
00:10:53,708 --> 00:10:55,250
when not fed with attention

259
00:10:55,958 --> 00:10:57,541
the more you practice this

260
00:10:57,541 --> 00:10:59,250
the more you'll start to notice the space

261
00:10:59,250 --> 00:11:00,750
between wanting something

262
00:11:00,958 --> 00:11:02,708
and deciding to pursue it

263
00:11:03,375 --> 00:11:04,375
that space

264
00:11:05,125 --> 00:11:06,916
that's where your freedom lives

265
00:11:11,583 --> 00:11:15,000
now let's talk about Mara's second daughter Arati

266
00:11:15,125 --> 00:11:18,000
her name translates to boredom or discontent

267
00:11:18,333 --> 00:11:20,041
and she might be the quietest

268
00:11:20,375 --> 00:11:22,416
yet most dangerous of the three

269
00:11:23,000 --> 00:11:24,208
while her sister Tanhā

270
00:11:24,208 --> 00:11:25,833
makes you chase what you don't have

271
00:11:26,041 --> 00:11:28,875
Arati makes you dissatisfied with what you do have

272
00:11:28,916 --> 00:11:30,416
she's that voice whispering

273
00:11:30,458 --> 00:11:33,625
is this all there is this is boring

274
00:11:33,958 --> 00:11:35,625
there must be something better

275
00:11:37,166 --> 00:11:38,625
in the ancient texts

276
00:11:38,750 --> 00:11:40,958
Buddha described Arati as a force that creates

277
00:11:40,958 --> 00:11:42,916
restlessness and discontentment

278
00:11:43,208 --> 00:11:44,791
and if you look closely

279
00:11:45,000 --> 00:11:47,000
you'll see her fingerprints everywhere

280
00:11:47,000 --> 00:11:48,250
in modern life

281
00:11:48,875 --> 00:11:52,250
Arati murmurs this meditation is pointless

